Your return statement is before the if block, therefore the method will return the value and the if block always won&#39;t get called.
The if block should be before the return statement.

For the range verification simply add this if block:

    Integer val = rand.nextInt();
    if (val &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; val &lt;= 33) {
    // in range;
}

You have a `return` statement just before the `if` block. When you execute a `return` from a Java method, the method execution ends from there and returns back to the caller of the method. So your `if` block will never execute, hence the **unreachable code**. 

For the range check, you can define it as 2 conditions.

 1. First condition to check if the value is equal or greater than 0 (`value &gt;= 0`)
 2. Second condition to check if the value is equal or less than 33 (`value &lt;= 33`)

Then combine them using AND (`&amp;&amp;`) operator as follows.

        Random rand = new Random();
        int value = rand.nextInt(101); //83
        if ((value &gt;= 0) &amp;&amp; (value &lt;= 33)) {
            // Do something
        }

The `unreachable code` is because your `if` statement is written after the `return` statement.

regarding the range of integers you can always check that a specific value is within this range
```
if (value &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; value &lt; 33){
    //do something
}
```

There are *multiple* issues with your posted code, but we can fix them fairly easily. First, your `main()` method currently would only display one value; add a loop - and if you expect to see a letter, then `computeRandom()` should return a `char` (not an `int`).

	public static void main(String args[]) {
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
			System.out.println(&quot;Random Integers: &quot; + computeRandom());
		}
	}

You shouldn&#39;t construct the `Random` in your `computeRandom` method, it&#39;s highly likely that invoking that in a loop will compute the same *seed* multiple times (so your random numbers wouldn&#39;t be random). Construct it once as a `static` field (as here), or pass it as an argument to `computeRandom()`. Next, to test for the range `0 - 33` you only need to test that your value (which you should save, because each call to `Random.nextInt()` *should* return a different value) is less than 34 (since `value` is in the range `0 - 100`). Finally, you should return something when the value is not in the desired range; you want `A` on valid so I chose `B` for not-valid. Like,

	private static final Random _RANDOM = new Random();

	public static char computeRandom() {
		// Generate random integers in range 0 to 100
		int val = _RANDOM.nextInt(101);
		if (val &lt; 34) {
			return &#39;A&#39;;
		}
		return &#39;B&#39;;
	}

If you didn&#39;t know that `value` already had a lower-bound of `0` you would want a logical and with the `if`. Like,

    if (val &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; val &lt;= 33) {
        return &#39;A&#39;;
    }

